    statement;The above example is equivalent to:while (true)
    statement;This might be a little unexpected, as you’d probably expect an omitted condition-expression to be treated asfalse. However, the C++ standard explicitly (and inconsistently) defines that an omitted condition-expression in a for-loop should be treated astrue.We recommend avoiding this form of the for loop altogether and usingwhile (true)instead.For-loops with multiple countersAlthough for-loops typically iterate over only one variable, sometimes for-loops need to work with multiple variables. To assist with this, the programmer can define multiple variables in the init-statement, and can make use of the comma operator to change the value of multiple variables in the end-expression:#include <iostream>

